RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) — instead of relying only on what an LLM learned during training, it retrieves relevant chunks 
from your own documents (via a vector database) and feeds them to the model as context before it answers.

This lets the model answer questions using your specific data (notes, docs, PDFs) accurately, without needing to retrain or fine-tune the 
model itself — like what we just built with your interview files + Llama3 + ChromaDB.

What's happening:

• llama3 (the model) is frozen — same weights every time, doesn't change based on your conversations

• Your docs/ folder gets re-read and re-embedded only when you explicitly run python rag.py ingest

• Each time you ask a question, it does a fresh search through your existing embeddings — it's not accumulating new knowledge or getting "smarter" from past questions

Analogy for your context: think of it like Grafana querying Prometheus — Prometheus doesn't "learn" from queries, it just stores data and answers questions against it. Same here: Chroma stores your document embeddings, Llama3 just retrieves + summarizes. No training happens during use.

For it to actually "learn" new information, you'd need to:

1. Add new files to docs/

2. Manually re-run:
   python rag.py ingest

