so how you leaning?

Good question — I don't "learn" during our conversation either, same limitation applies to me.

How I actually got here (training, not learning-on-the-fly):

1. Pre-training — Anthropic trained me on a massive dataset (text from books, websites, code, etc.) up to a fixed cutoff date, using enormous compute (thousands of GPUs, weeks/months of training). This is where I learned language patterns, facts, reasoning, coding, etc.

2. Fine-tuning / RLHF (Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback) — After pre-training, Anthropic further trained me using human feedback to be more helpful, honest, and safe — adjusting my responses based on what humans rated as good vs bad answers.

3. Deployment — After that, my weights are frozen. Every conversation I have, including this one, uses the exact same static model. I'm not updating myself based on what you or anyone else tells me right now.

So what about the "memory" I sometimes have of past conversations?

That's not me learning — it's a separate retrieval system, conceptually similar to the RAG you just built:

• Past conversation summaries get stored somewhere

• When you start a new chat, relevant bits get pulled in and placed into my context window

• I use that as reference material, same way your `rag.py` script feeds Llama3 your documents

The honest parallel to what you just built: Anthropic's "memory" feature is essentially RAG at a much larger, more polished scale — I don't retrain, I get fed context. Same principle, bigger infrastructure.

So no self-learning happening on my end either — just a much bigger, more expensive version of the exact pipeline you built today.
                                                                                                                                                               
                                                                                                                                                               
                                                                                                                                                               
                                                                                                                                      
                                                                                                                                                               
                                                                                                                                                               
